  100. (*        Relational format types

  102. In the first format+gadts implementation, the type for %(..%) in the
  103. fmt GADT was as follows:

  105. | Format_subst :                                           (* %(...%) *)
  106.     pad_option * ('d1, 'q1, 'd2, 'q2) reader_nb_unifier *
  107.     ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd1, 'q1, 'u) fmtty *
  108.     ('u, 'b, 'c, 'q1, 'e1, 'f) fmt ->
  109.       (('x, 'b, 'c, 'd2, 'q2, 'u) format6 -> 'x, 'b, 'c, 'd1, 'e1, 'f) fmt

  111. Notice that the 'u parameter in 'f position in the format argument
  112. (('x, .., 'u) format6 -> ..) is equal to the 'u parameter in 'a
  113. position in the format tail (('u, .., 'f) fmt). This means that the
  114. type of the expected format parameter depends of where the %(...%)
  115. are in the format string:

  117.   # Printf.printf "%(%)"
  118.   - : (unit, out_channel, unit, '_a, '_a, unit)
  119.       CamlinternalFormatBasics.format6 -> unit
  120.   = <fun>
  121.   # Printf.printf "%(%)%d"
  122.   - : (int -> unit, out_channel, unit, '_a, '_a, int -> unit)
  123.       CamlinternalFormatBasics.format6 -> int -> unit
  124.   = <fun>

  126. On the contrary, the legacy typer gives a clever type that does not
  127. depend on the position of %(..%) in the format string. For example,
  128. %(%) will have the polymorphic type ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a): it can
  129. be concatenated to any format type, and only enforces the constraint
  130. that its 'a and 'f parameters are equal (no format arguments) and 'd
  131. and 'e are equal (no reader argument).

  133. The weakening of this parameter type in the GADT version broke user
  134. code (in fact it essentially made %(...%) unusable except at the last
  135. position of a format). In particular, the following would not work
  136. anymore:

  138.   fun sep ->
  139.     Format.printf "foo%(%)bar%(%)baz" sep sep

  141. As the type-checker would require two *incompatible* types for the %(%)
  142. in different positions.

  144. The solution to regain a general type for %(..%) is to generalize this
  145. technique, not only on the 'd, 'e parameters, but on all six
  146. parameters of a format: we introduce a "relational" type
  147.   ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  148.    'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel
  149. whose values are proofs that ('a1, .., 'f1) and ('a2, .., 'f2) morally
  150. correspond to the same format type: 'a1 is obtained from 'f1,'b1,'c1
  151. in the exact same way that 'a2 is obtained from 'f2,'b2,'c2, etc.

  153. For example, the relation between two format types beginning with a Char
  154. parameter is as follows:

  156. | Char_ty :                                                 (* %c  *)
  157.     ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  158.      'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel ->
  159.     (char -> 'a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  160.      char -> 'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel

  162. In the general case, the term structure of fmtty_rel is (almost[1])
  163. isomorphic to the fmtty of the previous implementation: every
  164. constructor is re-read with a binary, relational type, instead of the
  165. previous unary typing. fmtty can then be re-defined as the diagonal of
  166. fmtty_rel:

  168.   type ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmtty =
  169.        ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f,
  170.         'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmtty_rel

  172. Once we have this fmtty_rel type in place, we can give the more
  173. general type to %(...%):

  175. | Format_subst :                                           (* %(...%) *)
  176.     pad_option *
  177.     ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l,
  178.      'g2, 'b, 'c, 'j2, 'd, 'a) fmtty_rel *
  179.     ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  180.     (('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) format6 -> 'g2, 'b, 'c, 'j2, 'e, 'f) fmt

  182. We accept any format (('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) format6) (this is
  183. completely unrelated to the type of the current format), but also
  184. require a proof that this format is in relation to another format that
  185. is concatenable to the format tail. When executing a %(...%) format
  186. (in camlinternalFormat.ml:make_printf or scanf.ml:make_scanf), we
  187. transtype the format along this relation using the 'recast' function
  188. to transpose between related format types.

  190.   val recast :
  191.      ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1) fmt
  192.   -> ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  193.       'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel
  194.   -> ('a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmt

  196. NOTE [1]: the typing of Format_subst_ty requires not one format type, but
  197. two, one to establish the link between the format argument and the
  198. first six parameters, and the other for the link between the format
  199. argument and the last six parameters.

  201. | Format_subst_ty :                                         (* %(...%) *)
  202.     ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l,
  203.      'g1, 'b1, 'c1, 'j1, 'd1, 'a1) fmtty_rel *
  204.     ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l,
  205.      'g2, 'b2, 'c2, 'j2, 'd2, 'a2) fmtty_rel *
  206.     ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  207.      'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel ->
  208.     (('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) format6 -> 'g1, 'b1, 'c1, 'j1, 'e1, 'f1,
  209.      ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) format6 -> 'g2, 'b2, 'c2, 'j2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel

  211. When we generate a format AST, we generate exactly the same witness
  212. for both relations, and the witness-conversion functions in
  213. camlinternalFormat do rely on this invariant. For example, the
  214. function that proves that the relation is transitive

  216.   val trans :
  217.      ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  218.       'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel
  219.   -> ('a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2,
  220.       'a3, 'b3, 'c3, 'd3, 'e3, 'f3) fmtty_rel
  221.   -> ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  222.       'a3, 'b3, 'c3, 'd3, 'e3, 'f3) fmtty_rel

  224. does assume that the two inputs have exactly the same term structure
  225. (and is only every used for argument witnesses of the
  226. Format_subst_ty constructor).
  227. *)

  229. (* Type of a block used by the Format pretty-printer. *)
  230. ‌type block_type =
  231.   | Pp_hbox   (* Horizontal block no line breaking *)

  233.   | Pp_hvbox  (* Horizontal-vertical block: same as vbox, except if this block

  239.                  when it leads to a new indentation of the current line *)
  240.   | Pp_fits   (* Internal usage: when a block fits on a single line *)

  338.        'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel ->
  339.       (('b1 -> 'c1) -> 'a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  340.        ('b2 -> 'c2) -> 'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel
  341.   | Any_ty :                                    (* Used for custom formats *)
  342.       ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  343.        'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel ->
  344.       ('x -> 'a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  345.        'x -> 'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel

  347.   (* Scanf specific constructor. *)
  348.   | Reader_ty :                                               (* %r  *)
  349.       ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  350.        'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel ->
  351.       ('x -> 'a1, 'b1, 'c1, ('b1 -> 'x) -> 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  352.        'x -> 'a2, 'b2, 'c2, ('b2 -> 'x) -> 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel
  353.   | Ignored_reader_ty :                                       (* %_r  *)
  354.       ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  355.        'a2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel ->
  356.       ('a1, 'b1, 'c1, ('b1 -> 'x) -> 'd1, 'e1, 'f1,
  357.        'a2, 'b2, 'c2, ('b2 -> 'x) -> 'd2, 'e2, 'f2) fmtty_rel

  359.   | End_of_fmtty :
  360.       ('f1, 'b1, 'c1, 'd1, 'd1, 'f1,
  361.        'f2, 'b2, 'c2, 'd2, 'd2, 'f2) fmtty_rel

  363. (***)

  365. (* List of format elements. *)
  366. ‌and ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt =
  367.   | Char :                                                   (* %c *)
  368.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  369.         (char -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  370.   | Caml_char :                                              (* %C *)
  371.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  372.         (char -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  373.   | String :                                                 (* %s *)
  374.       ('x, string -> 'a) padding * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  375.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  376.   | Caml_string :                                            (* %S *)
  377.       ('x, string -> 'a) padding * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  378.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  379.   | Int :                                                    (* %[dixXuo] *)
  380.       int_conv * ('x, 'y) padding * ('y, int -> 'a) precision *
  381.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  382.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  383.   | Int32 :                                                  (* %l[dixXuo] *)
  384.       int_conv * ('x, 'y) padding * ('y, int32 -> 'a) precision *
  385.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  386.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  387.   | Nativeint :                                              (* %n[dixXuo] *)
  388.       int_conv * ('x, 'y) padding * ('y, nativeint -> 'a) precision *
  389.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  390.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  391.   | Int64 :                                                  (* %L[dixXuo] *)
  392.       int_conv * ('x, 'y) padding * ('y, int64 -> 'a) precision *
  393.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  394.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  395.   | Float :                                                  (* %[feEgGFhH] *)
  396.       float_conv * ('x, 'y) padding * ('y, float -> 'a) precision *
  397.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  398.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  399.   | Bool :                                                   (* %[bB] *)
  400.       ('x, bool -> 'a) padding * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  401.         ('x, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  402.   | Flush :                                                  (* %! *)
  403.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  404.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt

  406.   | String_literal :                                         (* abc *)
  407.       string * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  408.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  409.   | Char_literal :                                           (* x *)
  410.       char * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  411.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt

  413.   | Format_arg :                                             (* %{...%} *)
  414.       pad_option * ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) fmtty *
  415.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  416.         (('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) format6 -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  417.   | Format_subst :                                           (* %(...%) *)
  418.       pad_option *
  419.       ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l,
  420.        'g2, 'b, 'c, 'j2, 'd, 'a) fmtty_rel *
  421.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  422.       (('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) format6 -> 'g2, 'b, 'c, 'j2, 'e, 'f) fmt

  424.   (* Printf and Format specific constructor. *)
  425.   | Alpha :                                                  (* %a *)
  426.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  427.         (('b -> 'x -> 'c) -> 'x -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  428.   | Theta :                                                  (* %t *)
  429.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  430.         (('b -> 'c) -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt

  432.   (* Format specific constructor: *)
  433.   | Formatting_lit :                                         (* @_ *)
  434.       formatting_lit * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  435.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  436.   | Formatting_gen :                                             (* @_ *)
  437.       ('a1, 'b, 'c, 'd1, 'e1, 'f1) formatting_gen *
  438.       ('f1, 'b, 'c, 'e1, 'e2, 'f2) fmt -> ('a1, 'b, 'c, 'd1, 'e2, 'f2) fmt

  440.   (* Scanf specific constructors: *)
  441.   | Reader :                                                 (* %r *)
  442.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  443.         ('x -> 'a, 'b, 'c, ('b -> 'x) -> 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  444.   | Scan_char_set :                                          (* %[...] *)
  445.       pad_option * char_set * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  446.         (string -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  447.   | Scan_get_counter :                                       (* %[nlNL] *)
  448.       counter * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  449.         (int -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  450.   | Scan_next_char :                                         (* %0c *)
  451.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  452.       (char -> 'a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt
  453.   | Ignored_param :                                          (* %_ *)
  454.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'y, 'x) ignored * ('x, 'b, 'c, 'y, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  455.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt

  457.   (* Custom printing format (PR#6452, GPR#140)

  459.      We include a type Custom of "custom converters", where an
  460.      arbitrary function can be used to convert one or more
  461.      arguments. There is no syntax for custom converters, it is only
  462.      intended for custom processors that wish to rely on the
  463.      stdlib-defined format GADTs.

  465.      For instance a pre-processor could choose to interpret strings
  466.      prefixed with ["!"] as format strings where [%{{ ... }}] is
  467.      a special form to pass a to_string function, so that one could
  468.      write:

  470.      {[
  471.        type t = { x : int; y : int }

  473.        let string_of_t t = Printf.sprintf "{ x = %d; y = %d }" t.x t.y

  475.        Printf.printf !"t = %{{string_of_t}}" { x = 42; y = 42 }
  476.      ]}
  477.   *)
  478.   | Custom :
  479.       ('a, 'x, 'y) custom_arity * (unit -> 'x) * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt ->
  480.       ('y, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt

  482.   (* end of a format specification *)
  483.   | End_of_format :
  484.         ('f, 'b, 'c, 'e, 'e, 'f) fmt

  486. (***)

  488. (* Type for ignored parameters (see "%_"). *)
  489. ‌and ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) ignored =
  490.   | Ignored_char :                                           (* %_c *)
  491.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  492.   | Ignored_caml_char :                                      (* %_C *)
  493.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  494.   | Ignored_string :                                         (* %_s *)
  495.       pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  496.   | Ignored_caml_string :                                    (* %_S *)
  497.       pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  498.   | Ignored_int :                                            (* %_d *)
  499.       int_conv * pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  500.   | Ignored_int32 :                                          (* %_ld *)
  501.       int_conv * pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  502.   | Ignored_nativeint :                                      (* %_nd *)
  503.       int_conv * pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  504.   | Ignored_int64 :                                          (* %_Ld *)
  505.       int_conv * pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  506.   | Ignored_float :                                          (* %_f *)
  507.       pad_option * prec_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  508.   | Ignored_bool :                                           (* %_B *)
  509.       pad_option -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  510.   | Ignored_format_arg :                                     (* %_{...%} *)
  511.       pad_option * ('g, 'h, 'i, 'j, 'k, 'l) fmtty ->
  512.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  513.   | Ignored_format_subst :                                   (* %_(...%) *)
  514.       pad_option * ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmtty ->
  515.         ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) ignored
  516.   | Ignored_reader :                                         (* %_r *)
  517.       ('a, 'b, 'c, ('b -> 'x) -> 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  518.   | Ignored_scan_char_set :                                  (* %_[...] *)
  519.       pad_option * char_set -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  520.   | Ignored_scan_get_counter :                               (* %_[nlNL] *)
  521.       counter -> ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored
  522.   | Ignored_scan_next_char :                                 (* %_0c *)
  523.       ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'd, 'a) ignored

  525. ‌and ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) format6 =
  526.   Format of ('a, 'b, 'c, 'd, 'e, 'f) fmt * string

  528. ‌‌let rec erase_rel : type a b c d e f g h i j k l .
  529.   (a, b, c, d, e, f,
  530.    g, h, i, j, k, l) fmtty_rel -> (a, b, c, d, e, f) fmtty
  531. = function
  532.   | Char_ty rest ->
  533.     Char_ty (erase_rel rest)
  534.   | String_ty rest ->
  535.     String_ty (erase_rel rest)
  536.   | Int_ty rest ->
  537.     Int_ty (erase_rel rest)
  538.   | Int32_ty rest ->
  539.     Int32_ty (erase_rel rest)
  540.   | Int64_ty rest ->
  541.     Int64_ty (erase_rel rest)
  542.   | Nativeint_ty rest ->
  543.     Nativeint_ty (erase_rel rest)
  544.   | Float_ty rest ->
  545.     Float_ty (erase_rel rest)
  546.   | Bool_ty rest ->
  547.     Bool_ty (erase_rel rest)
  548.   | Format_arg_ty (ty, rest) ->
  549.     Format_arg_ty (ty, erase_rel rest)
  550.   | Format_subst_ty (ty1, _ty2, rest) ->
  551.     Format_subst_ty (ty1, ty1, erase_rel rest)
  552.   | Alpha_ty rest ->
  553.     Alpha_ty (erase_rel rest)
  554.   | Theta_ty rest ->
  555.     Theta_ty (erase_rel rest)
  556.   | Any_ty rest ->
  557.     Any_ty (erase_rel rest)
  558.   | Reader_ty rest ->
  559.     Reader_ty (erase_rel rest)
  560.   | Ignored_reader_ty rest ->
  561.     Ignored_reader_ty (erase_rel rest)
  562.   | End_of_fmtty -> End_of_fmtty

  564. (******************************************************************************)
  565.                          (* Format type concatenation *)

  567. (* Concatenate two format types. *)
  568. (* Used by:
  569.    * reader_nb_unifier_of_fmtty to count readers in an fmtty,
  570.    * Scanf.take_fmtty_format_readers to extract readers inside %(...%),
  571.    * CamlinternalFormat.fmtty_of_ignored_format to extract format type. *)

  573. (*
  574. let rec concat_fmtty : type a b c d e f g h .
  575.     (a, b, c, d, e, f) fmtty ->
  576.     (f, b, c, e, g, h) fmtty ->
  577.     (a, b, c, d, g, h) fmtty =
  578. *)
  579. ‌let rec concat_fmtty :
  580. ‌  type a1 b1 c1 d1 e1 f1
  581.        a2 b2 c2 d2 e2 f2
  582.        g1 j1 g2 j2
  583.   .
  584.     (g1, b1, c1, j1, d1, a1,
  585.      g2, b2, c2, j2, d2, a2) fmtty_rel ->
  586.     (a1, b1, c1, d1, e1, f1,
  587.      a2, b2, c2, d2, e2, f2) fmtty_rel ->
  588.     (g1, b1, c1, j1, e1, f1,
  589.      g2, b2, c2, j2, e2, f2) fmtty_rel =
  590. fun fmtty1 fmtty2 -> match fmtty1 with
  591.   | Char_ty rest ->
  592.     Char_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  593.   | String_ty rest ->
  594.     String_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  595.   | Int_ty rest ->
  596.     Int_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  597.   | Int32_ty rest ->
  598.     Int32_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  599.   | Nativeint_ty rest ->
  600.     Nativeint_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  601.   | Int64_ty rest ->
  602.     Int64_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  603.   | Float_ty rest ->
  604.     Float_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  605.   | Bool_ty rest ->
  606.     Bool_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  607.   | Alpha_ty rest ->
  608.     Alpha_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  609.   | Theta_ty rest ->
  610.     Theta_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  611.   | Any_ty rest ->
  612.     Any_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  613.   | Reader_ty rest ->
  614.     Reader_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  615.   | Ignored_reader_ty rest ->
  616.     Ignored_reader_ty (concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  617.   | Format_arg_ty (ty, rest) ->
  618.     Format_arg_ty (ty, concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  619.   | Format_subst_ty (ty1, ty2, rest) ->
  620.     Format_subst_ty (ty1, ty2, concat_fmtty rest fmtty2)
  621.   | End_of_fmtty -> fmtty2

  623. (******************************************************************************)
  624.                            (* Format concatenation *)

  626. (* Concatenate two formats. *)
  627. ‌‌let rec concat_fmt : type a b c d e f g h .
  628.     (a, b, c, d, e, f) fmt ->
  629.     (f, b, c, e, g, h) fmt ->
  630.     (a, b, c, d, g, h) fmt =
  631. fun fmt1 fmt2 -> match fmt1 with
  632.   | String (pad, rest) ->
  633.     String (pad, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  634.   | Caml_string (pad, rest) ->
  635.     Caml_string (pad, concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  637.   | Int (iconv, pad, prec, rest) ->
  638.     Int (iconv, pad, prec, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  639.   | Int32 (iconv, pad, prec, rest) ->
  640.     Int32 (iconv, pad, prec, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  641.   | Nativeint (iconv, pad, prec, rest) ->
  642.     Nativeint (iconv, pad, prec, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  643.   | Int64 (iconv, pad, prec, rest) ->
  644.     Int64 (iconv, pad, prec, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  645.   | Float (fconv, pad, prec, rest) ->
  646.     Float (fconv, pad, prec, concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  648.   | Char (rest) ->
  649.     Char (concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  650.   | Caml_char rest ->
  651.     Caml_char (concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  652.   | Bool (pad, rest) ->
  653.     Bool (pad, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  654.   | Alpha rest ->
  655.     Alpha (concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  656.   | Theta rest ->
  657.     Theta (concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  658.   | Custom (arity, f, rest) ->
  659.     Custom (arity, f, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  660.   | Reader rest ->
  661.     Reader (concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  662.   | Flush rest ->
  663.     Flush (concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  665.   | String_literal (str, rest) ->
  666.     String_literal (str, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  667.   | Char_literal (chr, rest) ->
  668.     Char_literal   (chr, concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  670.   | Format_arg (pad, fmtty, rest) ->
  671.     Format_arg   (pad, fmtty, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  672.   | Format_subst (pad, fmtty, rest) ->
  673.     Format_subst (pad, fmtty, concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  675.   | Scan_char_set (width_opt, char_set, rest) ->
  676.     Scan_char_set (width_opt, char_set, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  677.   | Scan_get_counter (counter, rest) ->
  678.     Scan_get_counter (counter, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  679.   | Scan_next_char (rest) ->
  680.     Scan_next_char (concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  681.   | Ignored_param (ign, rest) ->
  682.     Ignored_param (ign, concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  684.   | Formatting_lit (fmting_lit, rest) ->
  685.     Formatting_lit (fmting_lit, concat_fmt rest fmt2)
  686.   | Formatting_gen (fmting_gen, rest) ->
  687.     Formatting_gen (fmting_gen, concat_fmt rest fmt2)

  689.   | End_of_format ->
  690.     fmt2
